1. _The entangled two-qubit state_ \(\varrho_{AB}\) _is compatible with a PT-moment vector_ \(\boldsymbol{p}^{(4)}\) _if and only if_ \[F(p_{2},p_{3})<p_{4}\leqslant F^{+}(p_{2},p_{3}),\quad\forall(p_{ 2},p_{3})\in\mathcal{A}.\] (3.20)
2. _The separable two-qubit state_ \(\varrho_{AB}\) _is compatible with a PT-moment vector_ \(\boldsymbol{p}^{(4)}\) _if and only if_ \[F^{-}(p_{2},p_{3})\leqslant p_{4}\leqslant F(p_{2},p_{3}),\quad\forall(p_{2}, p_{3})\in\mathcal{A}.\] (3.2 , it is equivalent to proving any two-qubit state_ \(\varrho_{AB}\) _is entangled if and only if the following inequality holds:_ \[p_{4}>F(p_{2},p_{3}),\] (3.22) _where_ \(F(p_{2},p_{3}):=\frac{3p_{2}^{2}-6p_{2}+8p_{3}+1}{6}\)_. This follows directly from the fact that_ \[\det(\varrho_{AB}^{\Gamma})=\frac{3p_{2}^{2}-6p_{2}+8p_{3}-6p_{4}+1}{4!}.\] (3.23)

It follows from [ 0 , 0 ] that \(\varrho_{AB}\) is entangled if and only if \(\det(\varrho_{AB}^{\Gamma})<0\). It follows that \(3p_{2}^{2}-6p_{2}+8p_{3}-6p_{4}+1<0\), and equivalently Eq. (3.22) holds. This completes the proof. \(\square\)__

According to Proposition 3.4 , we identify the dividing surface represented by \(p_{4}=F(p_{2},p_{3})\) which separates the whole 3D region of all two-qubit states into two parts corresponding to separable states and entangled states respectively.

